WHAT IS ICP
6.73 KB ‚Ä¢77 lines
‚Ä¢
Formatting may be inconsistent from source
ICP

It combines an academic/research component (for the framework, the theoretical concepts, the
methodology, data collection, etc‚Ä¶) and a strong professional approach (as it is a real-case
activities at executive-level).
ICP topics are based on executive level issues, for ex.:
‚óè Creation of a comprehensive business plan for a new activity (including ALL its
parts, from market analysis to financials),
‚óè Reorganisation plan for a distribution network,
‚óè Company rebranding and repositioning,
‚óè Market or product diversification,
‚óè Launch of a new product / entering into a new market, etc‚Ä¶
1. Objective
The ICP is a team project. It combines an academic/research component (for the framework, the theoretical concepts, the methodology, data collection, etc‚Ä¶) and a professional approach (as it is a real-case activities at executive-level).
The main objectives are:
1. To provide participants with a collaborative, multi-disciplinary, and intercultural work experience on a real-life executive challenge;
2. To put into practice the concepts and theory acquired during the Executive MBA with the support and guidance of an ESCP faculty member.
2. Outline
 In groups, participants are expected to perform an in-depth analysis of a situation, or a problemfaced by a real company and to define recommendations for actions that can realistically beimplemented by the business.
This 12-month team project allows participants to use and consolidate their understanding of the concepts and tools taught during the programme. The outcome of the ICP is a comprehensive report, which includes a series of recommendations at executive level that the sponsor company(corporate/institutional or entrepreneurial/start-up) can implement in order to meet the strategic challenge at hand.
The final report is defended in front of an academic jury. The presentation is made publicly orprivately according to the level of confidentiality required by the company sponsor.After the presentation/defense in front of the jury on the ICP day, each participant has to preparean individual academic paper, based on the results/data/findings of the ICP project.
TIMELINE
12 May 2025 at midnight: Final teams must be formed. 
End of June 2025: Tutors and alumni allocation completed. ICP project can officially start!
19 January 2026 (midnight): Progress report submission via the ICP platform
End of February 2026: Feedback from your tutor and the EMBA Dean on your mid-term progress
Jan‚ÄìMar 2026: Research Methods course (online, mostly asynchronous)
End of March 2026: Completion of the Research Methods MCQ test
20 May 2026: Submission of your final report on the platform
4 June 2026 (TBC): ICP Day ‚Äì online final presentation (1 hour per team; full attendance required)
16 July 2026: Submission of the individual academic paper by each team member
At the end of the ICP, you have to prepare:
1. A final report (one for the entire team)
2. A presentation for the ICP DAY
3. Each team member should prepare an individual paper, with an academic structure, to besubmitted after the ICP DAY. 
This INDIVIDUAL PAPER is the equivalent of your Master Thesis.
 The paper should have the following parts: 
abstract / Introduction / Literature review and background context / Methodology / Results and findings / Discussion / Conclusions. 
A specific seminar on ‚Äúresearch methods‚Äù will provide you more information and details on how to structure this paper. The paper should be based on the content of your ICP.
Each member of the team can pick one dimension ofthe ICP project and develop it in an academic-like manner
RENEW 2.0
ESCP Executive MBA - ICP
Summary
Re-New's first phase successfully validated the need for support in SME succession and established a strong foundation.
This second phase aims to build on this momentum by defining a sustainable business model, exploring monetization strategies and potential internationalization opportunities, and leveraging technology for efficient scaling.
The goal is to check if this is possible to transform Re-New from a purely pro bono initiative into a self-sustaining and impactful organization that accelerates and ensure success of SMEs transmissions.
Objectives of the ICP:
This ICP aims to address the challenges outlined above and develop a comprehensive plan for scaling Re-New into a thriving organization in France. Specific objectives include:
Develop a long-term sustainable Business Model: Determine the optimal organizational structure and operating model for Re-New (e.g., repreneurship accelerator, MBI fund, partnership with investment platforms).
Define Monetization Strategies: Explore various revenue streams, such as membership fees, success fees from successful acquisitions, corporate sponsorships, training program fees, sweat equity...
Identify potential synergies in candidate sourcing, due diligence, and investment deal structuring.
Create a Scalability Plan: Design a roadmap for expanding Re-New's operations, including team structure, technology infrastructure, and marketing strategy.
Leverage Technology Integration: Evaluate the potential of AI and other technologies to automate candidate matching, streamline support program delivery, and enhance decision-making.
Refine Value Proposition: Clearly articulate the unique value proposition of Re-New for repreneurs, investors, and SME owners in the French mark
Framework :
This ICP will employ a multi-faceted approach, including:
Market Research:
Analyze the competitive landscape of repreneurship accelerators, MBI funds, and SME advisory services in France.
Identify best practices in monetization and technology integration within the French context.
Assess the regulatory and legal requirements for operating in France.
Further research Prosperia and competing platforms for SME investment.
Stakeholder Interviews:
Conduct interviews with repreneurs, investors, SME owners, and industry experts in France to gather insights on market needs and preferences.
Validate potential business models and monetization strategies.
Specifically, explore collaboration opportunities with Prosperia, E&F, and investment funds.
Business Model Design:
Develop several business model options for Re-New, considering revenue streams, cost structure, and value proposition.
Evaluate the feasibility and scalability of each model.
Financial Modeling:
Create a financial model to project revenue, expenses, and profitability for different business model scenarios.
Determine the funding requirements for scaling Re-New.
Technology Assessment:
Identify potential AI and other technology solutions to automate and improve Re-New's operations.
Evaluate the cost-benefit of implementing these technologies.
Go-to-Market Strategy:
Develop a detailed go-to-market plan for Re-New, including target markets, marketing channels, and sales strategy specifically for the French market.